│ THOUGHT                                                                                                                      │
│ The repeated, identical compilation failures after every modification attempt strongly suggest an issue with the patching    │
│ process or the environment, rather than a logical error in the patch itself. The widespread syntax errors indicate that the  │
│ file is likely being corrupted. To circumvent this, I will adopt a different, more targeted approach.                        │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ My core idea for the fix has been consistent: to add a check in `isTreeTinyAndNotFullyVectorizable` to prevent the           │
│ vectorizer from processing invalid single-node reduction trees. The logic is sound, but the implementation is failing due to │
│ environmental issues.                                                                                                        │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ Instead of adding new blocks of code, which seems to be the source of the file corruption, I will modify an existing check.  │
│ The function `isFullyVectorizableTinyTree` is called from `isTreeTinyAndNotFullyVectorizable` and is a good candidate for    │
│ this modification.                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The current logic in `isFullyVectorizableTinyTree` is:                                                                       │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                       │
│ if (ForReduction)                                                                                                            │
│   return VectorizableTree.size() > 1;                                                                                        │
│ ```                                                                                                                          │
│ This means for a reduction, a tiny tree is considered "fully vectorizable" if its size is greater than 1. This is too        │
│ simplistic and allows a single-node tree (which is not a reduction) to fall through to the next checks.                      │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ I will modify this line to correctly handle the case of a single-node tree. A single-node tree is only a valid part of a     │
│ reduction if it's a "gather" of other values, which means it must have operands. If it has no operands, it's a scalar        │
│ constant and should not be considered vectorizable in a reduction context.                                                   │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ The modified logic will be:                                                                                                  │
│ ```cpp                                                                                                                       │
│ if (ForReduction)                                                                                                            │
│   return VectorizableTree.size() > 1 ||                                                                                      │
│          (VectorizableTree.size() == 1 &&                                                                                    │
│           VectorizableTree.back()->getNumOperands() > 0);                                                                    │
│ ```                                                                                                                          │
│ This change is a single-line modification, which is much less likely to cause file corruption. I will use `sed` to perform   │
│ this targeted replacement.                                                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                              │
│ ```bash                                                                                                                      │
│ sed -i 's/return VectorizableTree.size() > 1;/return VectorizableTree.size() > 1 || (VectorizableTree.size() == 1 \&\&       │
│ VectorizableTree.back()->getNumOperands() > 0);/' llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp                            │
│ ```                                                                                                                          │
